raoul@ATHENA.MIT.EDU (Nico Garcia) writes:

> Put it this way: when you buy a house and change the locks, do you
> give the hardware store salesclerks copies of your keys, so they can
> give them to the police if they get a warrant? Even if they'll sell
> you Medeco locks, which are almost impossible to pick, instead of the
> standard Yale locks which are fairly easy?

No, you don't have to escrow your house keys.

But this is only because locks with more than a one-inch bolt
throw are illegal.  (In California, probably other states, 
allowing the cops to readily force entry:  an apparent outcome of 
DOJ-recomended drug-war state legislation, I understand)

